      "narrative": "Across a 12-week simulation in a low-demand, low-growth market, none of the three baseline strategies generated revenue — a sobering result that highlights how difficult conversion is under current conditions. However, the Aggressive Growth strategy distinguished itself by producing the only quote in the dataset, driven by a deliberate stack of conversion levers: charm pricing, price anchoring, a 10% discount, loss-aversion messaging, twice-weekly campaign cadence, GPU category focus, and bundling. The Conservative Hold and Relationship Building strategies, while generating comparable lead volumes, failed to advance any prospect to the quote stage, suggesting that trust- and ROI-framed messaging without pricing pressure is insufficient to break buyer inertia. The strategic takeaway is clear: in constrained markets, activation tactics matter more than awareness tactics. That said, the aggressive approach carries real risks around margin erosion, segment concentration, and statistical fragility — a single quote is a directional signal, not proof. The recommended path forward is to adopt the aggressive playbook's conversion mechanics while broadening segment exposure and tightening discount governance to protect profitability.",
